>>> Welcome to Redsim ! <<<

Redsim (RSM) is a 3D circuit simulator written in C and OpenGL.

BUILDING RSM
	Currently, RSM uses the following libraries, some of which must be installed your system:
		GLFW (dependency)
		GLAD (included)
		stb_image (included)
		cglm (dependency)
		FreeType (dependency)
		usflib2 (dependency; can be found in my github)
	usflib2 must be compiled then symlinked in the redsim/ directory (same level as the Makefile).

	Then, simply run `make` to produce the executable.

INFORMATION
	RSM allows you to build complex circuits in 3D space, which can then be evaluated in-game at high speeds.

	RSM configuration options, such as keybinds or flyspeed, can be adjusted either through the in-game
	config command, the src/rsmlayout.c file (default states), or the include/rsmlayout.c file.

	For more details, refer to the in-game help command.

DEFAULT LAYOUT
	ESC to toggle mouse capture, or switch back to NORMAL mode
	CTRL+Q to save and exit

	WASD to move

	Left click to destroy
	Right click to place or interact
	Middle click to pipette
	'f' to force-place (hold)

	't' to open command prompt
	':' as command prefix
	CTRL+R to clear command log, or prompt if open

	Scroll wheel to change hotbar slots
	'0' to '9' to choose hotbar slot ('1' first, '0' last)
	'x' and 'z' to change hotbars (scroll forwards or backwards)

	'e' to open inventory
	Left click to interact with inventory

For a list of configuration options, such as sensitivity, flight speed, or render distance, consult
either src/rsmlayout.c, or src/command.c for their aliases.

REDSIM RULES
	RSM has 7 primitive components which you can use in conjunction with the 3D wire connection rules
	to form intricate circuits in space.

	All components in RSM connect through wires (except if they are next to each other, of course). Signals
	transported using wires decay at a natural rate of 1 signal strength (ss) per block, with the maximum
	ss value being 255, and the minimum being 0.

	First, it is important to understand the concept of "electrification" (block powering), which is central
	to how components in RSM connect together. There are two types of blocks: conductors and insulators.
	Conductors can be "powered" (electrified) in two ways: soft-powering and hard-power, whilst insulators
	can never be powered.

	Hard-powering is achieved when a component's primary output is pointed into a conductor.
		(Note: only the inverter has more than one output; see table below)
	Any wire touching the conductor will be powered as if the component were connected to it.
	Any component whose primary input touches the conductor will likewise be connected to it.
		(Note: secondary inputs cannot connect by electrification!)

	Soft-powering is achieved when a wire points into a conductor.
		(Note: wires soft-power the block underneath them, too)
	Any component whose primary input touches the conductor will be connected to the wire without signal decay.

	Below is a table of all RSM blocks and their usage.
	Entries begin with the internal name, followed by the pretty name (see blockmap for more details).
	=============================================================================================================
	RSM_BLOCK_AIR (air): Is an insulator. Cannot support components.

	RSM_BLOCK_SILICON (silicon_[type]): Is a conductor. May support components.

	RSM_BLOCK_GLASS (glass_[type]): Is an insulator. May support components.

	RSM_BLOCK_DIODE (diode_[type]): Is an insulator. May support components.
	Wires placed on top of diodes experience a "semi-connectivity"; if diode type is down, then signals may
	not propagate upwards from the wire place on the diode. The opposite is true: if diode type is up, then
	signals may not go down from the diode.
		(Note: signals can still come onto the diode from the opposite direction!)

	RSM_BLOCK_TARGET (target): Is a conductor. May support components.
	Wires placed next to a target will always point to it, and as such soft-power it.

	RSM_BLOCK_TRANSISTOR_ANALOG (transistor_analog_[state]): Is a component. Needs support from underneath.
	Output is the difference of ss between primary and max ss of secondary inputs, capped at 0.
		(Note: Secondary ss is subtracted from primary ss)

	RSM_BLOCK_TRANSISTOR_DIGITAL (transistor_digital_[state]): Is a component. Needs support from underneath.
	Output is primary input if max ss of secondary inputs is less than or equal to it, else it is 0.

	RSM_BLOCK_LATCH (latch_[state]): Is a component. Needs support from underneath.
	Output is ss currently stored in the storage buffer.
	If all secondary inputs are off, the mode is WRITE, and the primary input overwrites the storage buffer.
	Else, the mode is KEEP, and the primary input has no effect on the storage buffer.

	RSM_BLOCK_INVERTER (inverter_[type]_[state]): Is a component. Needs support either from underneath or side.
	Output is 255 if input is 0, else output is 0.
	Inverters will always hard-power up (primary output), but all other directions (save input direction) can
	be read from by wires and other components.

	RSM_BLOCK_BUFFER (buffer_[type]_[state]): Is a component. Needs support from underneath.
	Output is ss currently stored in the last serial storage buffer. All buffers shift forward to allow for
	output and the first is overwritten by the primary input.
	Can be set to 4 delay states (1 -> 2 -> 4 -> 8 ticks).

	RSM_BLOCK_RESISTOR (resistor): Is a conductor. May support components.
	Wires placed on top of a resistor will experience ss decay equivalent to the resistor setting + natural rate.
		(Note: block settings can be globally set with the ss command)

	RSM_BLOCK_CONSTANT_SOURCE_OPAQUE (constant_source_opaque): Is a component.
	RSM_BLOCK_CONSTANT_SOURCE_TRANS (constant_source_trans): Is a component.
	Output is constant source setting. Only components which directly read from a constant source are affected.
		(Note: constant sources, being components, cannot be electrified)

	RSM_BLOCK_LIGHT_DIGITAL (light_digital_[state]): Is a component.
	No output, but changes graphical state depending on powered status.

	RSM_BLOCK_WIRE (wire): Is special.
	Wires autoconnect to any other adjacent wires. This may affect which blocks they point to, although some
	blocks (and most components) can "redirect" wires, forcing them to point (and connect) to them.
	Wires may climb up or down blocks when placed diagonally, but cannot be placed vertically.
		(Note: wires can only climb when no conductors block the diagonal bend)
